    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-11-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-11-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="303"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>303. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, November
                    15, 1956<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d303fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Files, 740.5/11–1556. Limited Official Use. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_WCB1">Wood</persName> on November 20.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1956-11-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 15, 1956</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KC1">Constantine Karamanlis</persName> Prime Minister
                        of Greece</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGV1">George V. Melas</persName> Greek
                        Ambassador</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CPA1">Phendon Cavalierato</persName> Counselor, Greek
                        Embassy</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Robert Murphy</persName>, <gloss target="#t_G1"
                            >G</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">William M. Rountree</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">C. Burke Elbrick</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TBELIII1">B. E. L. Timmons</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_RA1">RA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JOT1">Owen T. Jones</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_GTI1">GTI</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WMW1">Murat W. Williams</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_GTI1">GTI</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WCB1">Chalmers B. Wood</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_GTI1">GTI</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName> stressed that our attitude
                    towards <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> was unchanged and that recent
                    events, especially in Hungary,<note n="2" xml:id="d303fn2">Reference is to the
                        Hungarian rebellion during the fall of 1956.</note> had underlined the
                    continuing need for <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>.</p>
                <p>The Prime Minister agreed on the need for <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>,
                    but said that it had been shaken by recent events. He emphasized the need for
                    strengthening <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> and suggested three general
                    needs for improvement: 1) The need to widen <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >NATO</gloss>’s duties to include political and economic questions, so that
                    the members would come to have the solidarity of a family with common peacetime
                    interests as well as the need of common defense in time of danger. 2) Cyprus is
                    a weakness. “We are in one alliance, but we don’t have the ability or perhaps
                    the courage to tackle this question between three members.”<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d303fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KC1">Karamanlis</persName> discussed Cyprus with
                            <persName corresp="#p_HJC2">Holmes</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_TRL1">Thurston</persName> on October 5; see <ref
                            target="#d200">Document 200</ref>.</note> Three members have a public
                    dispute which can’t be settled. This is bad for <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >NATO</gloss>’s reputation. 3) The recent Anglo-French action in Egypt<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d303fn4">Reference is to the Anglo-French air bombardment of
                        Egyptian installations in the fall of 1956.</note> is disruptive for <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>. Many members of <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >NATO</gloss> disapproved of these actions. If some procedure can’t be found
                    for settling these disagreements, the US should take the lead and attempt to
                    “discipline” some of the members by “persuasion”. The US is in a good position
                    to do this since its prestige was never higher.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName> agreed that something needed to
                    be done, but indicated the difficulties especially if the United States appeared
                    to try and force other members. He hoped that the report of the Three <pb
                        facs="0608" n="578" xml:id="pg_578"/> Wise Men<note n="5" xml:id="d303fn5"
                        >Reference is to the committee of three appointed by the Intergovernmental
                        Conference for the Common Market and <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1"
                            >EURATOM</gloss> in late October 1956.</note> would contain some
                    suggestions. He pointed out that the members were democracies which did not take
                    lightly to dictation. He suggested that formal debates in the North Atlantic
                    Council would not be apt to settle differences and suggested that the United
                    States could be more useful by informally offering its good offices.</p>
                <p>The Prime Minister said he was not attempting to make specific suggestions but
                    commented that any democracy which joined an alliance must surrender some of its
                    sovereignty. Democracy must not be allowed to drift into license.</p>
            </div>
